[lesson title="Drawing a Rectangle"]

We'll use code created by others like we did in the previous lesson. This time, we'll solve a more complicated problem: drawing shapes.

[title]Meet the turtle[/title]

We present you: the turtle! We created the turtle to teach you how to call functions.

[visual path="visuals/TurtleHello.tscn"]

The turtle is a little machine that moves forward, turns, and draws lines along its path.

To make it draw, you give it a list of instructions: on each code line, you call one specific function.

We prepared several functions for you:

- [code]move_forward(pixels)[/code] makes the turtle move forward over a given distance in [i]pixels[/i].  
- [code]turn_right(degrees)[/code] makes the turtle turn clockwise by a precise amount of [i]degrees[/i].
- [code]turn_left(degrees)[/code] works the same as [code]turn_right(degrees)[/code], except the turtle turns counter-clockwise.

You'll use these functions the same way you used [code]rotate()[/code] before.

The turtle draws a white line as it moves. We'll use this line to draw shapes.

For example, to move the turtle 200 pixels, you would write [code]move_forward(200)[/code].

[visual path="visuals/ExampleMoveForward.tscn"]

[title]Turning left and right[/title]

The functions [code]turn_left()[/code] and [code]turn_right()[/code] work the same.

To turn 45 degrees to the right, you would write [code]turn_right(45)[/code].

If we call [code]turn_right(45)[/code], the turtle turns 45 degrees to the right before moving on to the next instruction.

[visual path="visuals/ExampleRotate.tscn"]

Using these instructions, we can make any two-dimensional shape we like!

Try to understand the example below. 

In the next practice, you'll use the functions we saw above to first draw a corner, then a rectangle like this one.

[visual path="visuals/ExampleRectangle.tscn"]

[quiz_choice question="In the function call below, which part is the argument?" multiple="false" shuffle="true"]
[code]move_forward(30)[/code]
[option]move_forward[/option]
[option correct]30[/option]
[explanation]A function's arguments are all the values inside the parentheses. In this case, there's only one, but there can be multiple separated by commas.

In this case, [code]move_forward[/code] is the function's name and [code]30[/code] is the argument.

This function call will make the turtle move forward by [code]30[/code] pixels.[/explanation]
[/quiz_choice]

[title]The turtle uses code made specifically for this app![/title]

The turtle is a little learning tool custom-made for this course, based on a proven code learning methodology. It's designed to teach you how to use and create functions.

So please don't be surprised if writing code like [code]turn_left()[/code] inside of the Godot editor doesn't work! And don't worry, once you've learned the foundations, you'll see they make it faster and easier to learn Godot functions.

Let's move on to practice! You'll get to play with the turtle functions to draw shapes.

[practice id="res://course/lesson-4-drawing-a-rectangle/practice-Gx0c7DDi.tres" title="Drawing a Corner"]
[description]Use the turtle to draw a square's corner. You'll then build upon it to draw a rectangle.[/description]
[goal]
In this practice, we'll tell the turtle to draw a corner.

The corner is made up of two lines that are [code]200[/code] pixels long. The lines are connected at each end by [code]90[/code] degrees, or right-angle.

The [code]move_forward()[/code] and [code]turn_right()[/code] functions to the right draw a corner, but they're missing some arguments.

Add the missing arguments so the turtle moves forward [code]200[/code] pixels, turns right [code]90[/code] degrees, then moves forward again [code]200[/code] pixels.

We added the first argument for you so the turtle moves forward [code]200[/code] pixels.

In the following practices, we'll draw multiple corners to create rectangles.
[/goal]
[starting_code]
func draw_corner():
	move_forward(200)
	turn_right()
	move_forward()
[/starting_code]
